register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruce","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a place in Normandy, probably from Brix (La Manche).","Altered form of French   Brousse  .","History: The son of the Domesday baron, a friend of David I of Scotland, was granted by him the Lordship of Annandale in 1124, and his second son Robert became the founder of the Scottish house of Bruce. — This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with its original form <i>Brousse</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Brusse","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Brussé</b>): from French   Brousse  . This form of the surname is also found in France."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":10,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":19,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Anne de Grousse was born in 1205, in Dresden, Amt Dresden, Saxony. She married Robert de Hill in 1220, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1254, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 49, and was buried in Nash, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1205–1254":"1205–1254","1199–1264":"1199–1264","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1654":"1654","1224":"1224","1254":"1254","1199":"1199","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","Dresden, Dresden, Saxony, Germany":"Dresden, Amt Dresden, Sachsen","St. John the Baptist Churchyard, Nash, Shropshire, England":"Nash, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Court of Hill, Nash, Shropshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1205–1254":"1205–1254","1199–1264":"1199–1264","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1654":"1654","1224":"1224","1254":"1254","1199":"1199","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","Dresden, Dresden, Saxony, Germany":"Dresden, Amt Dresden, Sachsen","St. John the Baptist Churchyard, Nash, Shropshire, England":"Nash, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Court of Hill, Nash, Shropshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1205–1254":"1205–1254","1199–1264":"1199–1264","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1206":"1206","